ns":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFree fatty acids are versatile molecules that can undergo several metabolic pathways in the body. One of the key fates is their \u003Cstrong\u003Eincorporation into phospholipids\u003C/strong\u003E, which are essential components of cell membranes. This process is crucial for maintaining cell structure and function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion to glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is not possible as free fatty acids are metabolised to acetyl-CoA, which cannot enter gluconeogenesis. \u003Cstrong\u003EExcretion unchanged in urine\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur as free fatty acids are not significantly excreted in urine but are either utilised or stored. \u003Cstrong\u003EConversion to amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E cannot occur as free fatty acids lack the nitrogen-containing precursors required for amino acid synthesis. \u003Cstrong\u003EStorage as glycogen\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as free fatty acids are stored as triglycerides in adipose tissue, not as glycogen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important fates of free fatty acids include beta-oxidation for energy production, conversion to ketone bodies during fasting, and synthesis of signalling molecules like eicosanoids.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Free fatty acids can be converted into triglycerides for storage in adipose tissue","Free fatty acids can be oxidised in mitochondria to produce ATP for energy","Free fatty acids can be incorporated into phospholipids for cell membrane synthesis","Free fatty acids can be converted into ketone bodies in the liver during fasting","Free fatty acids can be used to synthesise eicosanoids for cell signalling"],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 69; pg. 854","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952.","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97358"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17864"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97358"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:45:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:45:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10578"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115355"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},